{
  "version": 2,
  "name": "Cymatics",
  "description": "Chladni plate simulation: sand settles onto the nodal lines of a standing wave, and changing the mode numbers physically rearranges it. The plate field is the closed-form Chladni pattern sin(nπx)sin(mπy) ± sin(mπx)sin(nπy), built from four projected sine terms multiplied and combined in both symmetry families. Sand particles feel a force toward the nodal lines (the gradient of the negated absolute field) and a Brownian jiggle whose strength is modulated by the field itself — sand vibrates violently on loud regions of the plate and freezes on the quiet lines, which is the physical tell of the real experiment. Density accumulates through draw/resolve, persists through a decaying trail loop, and grades through the Log tone curve into a warm sand gradient over a near-black plate. Mode X / Mode Y are prime modulation targets (bind pitch or bands); Cycle Modes walks a curated (n,m) table on clip triggers.",
